# PacePal Running Knowledge Base

## Beginner Running
Beginner runners should start with 2 to 4 runs per week and increase gradually.
Easy pace should feel conversational.

## Easy Runs
Easy runs build aerobic fitness and should feel comfortable.
Most weekly mileage should be done at an easy effort.

## Tempo Runs
Tempo runs are sustained efforts at a comfortably hard pace.
They help improve lactate threshold and endurance.

## Interval Runs
Intervals are short repeated efforts with recovery between reps.
They are used to improve speed and aerobic capacity.

## Long Runs
Long runs help build endurance and are usually done once per week.
They should usually be completed at an easy effort.

## Glute Pain Guidance
If glute pain is sharp, worsening, or changes running form, reduce or stop running.
Low impact alternatives such as walking or elliptical may be better until symptoms improve.
If pain is severe or persists, seek medical advice.

## Cross Training
Elliptical, cycling, and walking can maintain fitness while reducing impact.
Cross training is useful during recovery or mild injury periods.

## Recovery
Recovery includes sleep, hydration, easy movement, and rest days.
Soreness may be normal, but sharp or worsening pain is not.

## Warm Up
A warm up before running can include leg swings, glute activation, and light walking or jogging.

## Cool Down
A cool down after running can include walking and gentle stretching.
